Plutarch (Pompeius, c. 43) says that when Pompeius was return- ing victorious from the East, and people were expecting that “a monarchy would be firmly established, Crassus taking his sons and his money secretly got away from Rome, whether it was that he was really afraid, or, what is more probable, he wished to give credibility to the calumny and to strengthen the odium against Pompeius.'’ Crassus went abroad as a private person, but so great a man could have the use of a provincial fleet.
